import datetime

from IPython.display import Image

AI Project 2020-2021

Hoping to predict a ships destination and its trajectory time delta.

Wouldnt it be great if we could predict a ships destination ? In this paper I will try to tackle this challenge.

For input there is an unprocessed dataset containing a ships ID and its total trajectory. The data isnt always that accurate since a ships owner will sometimes cancel its ships beacon, meaning it wont send out its location data.

This project is divided into two parts.

First the data will be processed. This will be done through two steps.The first step is to split the data based on a time delta.

You have to ask yourself these question, why is the time difference between two registries sometimes a big difference ? and When would an owner stop the beacon from sending location data ? The answer is that the owner will stop the transmitting of the beacon when he is asleep or docked. This ofcourse makes the data inaccurate. Thats why I first split the dataset on a timedelta. This will make sure that the total trajectory of a ship will be split into real trajectories.

The next split will be done based on how fast the ship is moving. If it is moving below a certain threshold (this cant be zero because the current cant be dismissed), the ship most likely has stopped and reached its destination, meaning we have to split on this point.

The second part is training a neural network to predict a ships end destination and time traveled between start and end destination. To train this neural network, I need to be sure the data is in the correct format. The preferable format is the ships start position (latitude and longitude), the ships end position (latitude and longitude) and the time delta between the two positions.

Processing the unprocessed data

Disclaimer; Please compile the first part of this process through the AIproject_Notebook.ipynb file, in a visual studio code environment. I put the code here for readability, but the python code will not compile correctly in an R studio environment.

unprocessed = pd.read_csv("schipsdataset.csv",sep=';')
unprocessed.head(10)

Changeable variables to alter the output file. If you believe the time delta when the owner puts off the beacon is shorter or longer, this can be adjusted here. This can also be done with the speed delta.

timedelta = 36000 #1 hour
speedDelta = 2     #2 meter per second
f = open("schipsdataset.csv")
fileData = f.readlines()
List = []
outputList = []
def getTime(tuple):
    return (tuple[0]*60) + tuple[1]
data = []
for d in fileData:
    temp = d.replace(";",",")
    data.append(temp.split(","))
  
List.append(data[1])
def splitList(List):
    if(len(List)<1):
        return 0
    newList = []
    newList.append(List[0])
    route = 1
    for i in range(1,len(List)):
        
        if(len(List[i]) > 7):
            if((not (List[i][7]=="") )and (not(newList[len(newList)-1][7] == "") )):
                if((not (List[i][7]=="NULL") )and (not(newList[len(newList)-1][7] == "NULL") )):
                    if(not (List[i][7].rstrip("\n") is None)):
                        if(not (newList[len(newList)-1][7].rstrip("\n") is None)):
                                speedDiff = int(List[i][7]) - int(newList[len(newList)-1][7])
                                if(speedDiff < speedDelta):
                                    newList.append(List[i])
                                else:
                                    d = []
                                    d.append(newList[0][0])
                                    d.append(route)
                                    route = route + 1
                                    d.append(newList[0][2] + "." +newList[0][3])
                                    d.append(newList[0][4] + "." +newList[0][5])
                                    
                                    d.append(newList[len(newList)-1][2] + "."+newList[len(newList)-1][3])
                                    d.append(newList[len(newList)-1][4] + "."+newList[len(newList)-1][5])
                                                                        
                                    
                                    time1 = datetime.datetime.strptime(newList[0][1], '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S.%f')
                                    time2 = datetime.datetime.strptime(newList[len(newList)-1][1], '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S.%f')
                                    timeDiff = time2 - time1
                                    tup = divmod(timeDiff.total_seconds(), 60)    
                                    d.append(getTime(tup))
                                    print(d)
                                    outputList.append(d)
                                    newList = []
                                    newList.append(List[i])
for i in range(2,len(data)):
    time1 = datetime.datetime.strptime(List[len(List)-1][1], '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S.%f')
    time2 = datetime.datetime.strptime(data[i][1], '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S.%f')
    timeDiff = time2 - time1
    tup = divmod(timeDiff.total_seconds(), 60)
    if(getTime(tup) < timedelta):
        if(len(data[i])>7):
            List.append(data[i])
    else:
        splitList(List)
        List = []
List.append(data[i])
with open('output.csv', mode='w') as output_file:
    output_writer = csv.writer(output_file, delimiter=',', quotechar='"', quoting=csv.QUOTE_MINIMAL)
    for data in outputList:        
        output_writer.writerow(data)

The dataset has been splitted and it is now time to delete null values and place column names.

sdata = pd.read_csv("output.csv",sep=',',names=["shipid","routeid","startLongitude","startLatitude","endlongitude","endlatitude","timedelta"])
sdata=sdata[sdata.timedelta!=0]
sdata=sdata[sdata.timedelta>0]
sdata.head(10)
sdata.to_csv(r'processeddata.csv',sep='\t', index=False)

The data has now been processed. From here on the code will compile in R studio.

Each ships route is now a single row, with its ID, starting latitude & longitude and its end latitude & longitude. The time delta between two destinations is also included.

Now its time to start exploring neural networks.

The goal is to hopefully accurately predict a correct destinations latitude and longitude, based on the start latitude and longitude. This will be achieved by training the model on the thousands of trajects that happened in the past.

pdata <- read.csv("processeddata.csv", sep = "")

Neural networks

Predicting the ships destination

First we need to split the dataset into training and test sets. The model will be trained on the trained set, and then the model can start predicting on the test set. The training control needs to be defined.

There are lots of neural networks. The first one is the nnet neural network. A neural network classifier is a software system that predicts the value of a categorical value.

By setting the seed, the partition will be reproducible.

pdata = pdata[1:10000,]
set.seed(1)
smp_size <- floor(0.70 * nrow(pdata))
train_ind <- sample(seq_len(nrow(pdata)), size = smp_size)
train <- pdata[train_ind, ]
test <- pdata[-train_ind, ]
train_control <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", repeats = 3)

Building the neural network for the longitude.

nn_Lon <- train(endlongitude ~ startLongitude + startLatitude + timedelta ,
               data = train,
               trControl = train_control,
               method = "nnet", 
               linout = TRUE)

The next neural network will be the K-nearest neighbor algorithm network.

This network is a supervised machine learning algorithm. KNN works by finding the distances between a query and all the examples in the data, selecting the specified number examples (K) closest to the query, then it votes for the most frequent label or the averages of the labels.

An analogy for KNN is; show me your friends, and Ill tell you who you are.

First we train the model on the training set.

model_Lon <- train(endlongitude ~ startLongitude + startLatitude + timedelta ,
                   data = train,
                   trControl = train_control,
                   method = "knn", 
                   preProcess = c("center","scale"), tuneLength = 20)
model_Lon

Predicting the time delta

The next goal is to make neural networks to accurately predict the time delta between a ships starting positioning and a ships destination positioning.

The time delta in this context is the time traveled between the two places.

First we build the nnet neural network.

nn_time <- train(timedelta ~ startLongitude + startLatitude + endlatitude + endlongitude ,
               data = train,
               trControl = train_control,
               method = "nnet", 
               linout = TRUE)

K-nearest neighbor algorithm network:

model_knn_timedelta <- train(timedelta ~ startLongitude + startLatitude + endlatitude + endlongitude ,
                   data = train,
                   trControl = train_control,
                   method = "knn", 
                   preProcess = c("center","scale"), tuneLength = 20)

Conclusion:

The goal of this project was hoping to be able to predict if it was possible to determine a ships destination and the time traveled in a ships route.

Through nnet and KNN it was possible to accurately predict a ships destination positioning. This was done through training the model on past trajectories.

The time delta has also been predicted, but this was not as accurate as the ships destination positioning.
